text:
Chained Redirects (Redirect to Redirect). A web app redirects a user via an internal endpoint, which then redirects again based on an unvalidated parameter. Attackers exploit this chain to hide malicious targets behind multiple trusted-looking URLs. Users see only the first trusted domain before being forwarded through a second, potentially malicious domain—making detection difficult and phishing more convincing. ### 🟢 Step 1: Understand the Risk- Redirect chains involve two or more redirects in sequence.- Attackers can embed malicious URLs deeper in the chain to evade simple detection.- Users initially see trusted domains before final malicious target.---### 🟢 Step 2: Build Safe Lab Environment1. Create step1.php:php
<?php
$next = $_GET['next'];
header("Location: step2.php?redirectTo=$next");
exit;
5 Run via php -S localhost:80002. Create step2.php:php
<?php
$url = $_GET['redirectTo'];
header("Location: $url");
exit;
---### 🟢 Step 3: Test Legitimate FlowOpen browser:[URL] Redirects via step2 to /welcome.html successfully.---### 🟢 Step 4: Simulate AttackVisit:[URL] Browser chain-redirects: step1 → step2 → evil.com. Each redirect appears trusted until the final step.---### 🟢 Step 5: Observe via cURL or BurpcURL:curl -IL "[URL]"HTTP/1.1 302 FoundLocation: step2.php?redirectTo=[URL]"HTTP/1.1 302 FoundLocation: [URL]"Burp Suite: intercept and inspect both redirect steps.---### 🟢 Step 6: Real‑World ScenarioLarge corporations often chain redirects for tracking or analytics:- trusted.com/track?next=trusted.com/go?redirect=[URL] Look benign initially but end at phishing domain.---### 🟢 Step 7: Impact- Deep phishing: Users feel more secure due to perceived trusted URLs.- Bypasses simple scanners that only check first-level redirects.- Credential theft, malware delivery.---### 🟢 Step 8: Detection- Trace all redirect steps manually or via tools like Burp.- Use scanners that analyze multiple redirects (OWASP ZAP, Burp active scan).- Code reviews to detect chained use of header("Location") or redirect functions.---### 🟢 Step 9: Fixes- Validate each redirect step against a full whitelist of safe URLs.- Eliminate unnecessary chaining—redirect directly or map using a trusted ID.- Insert confirmation pages if necessary: “You're leaving trusted.com. Continue to final destination?”- Log all redirect usage to detect abuse.✅ Once chained validation is applied, even hidden malicious targets are blocked. Tools: Browser, PHP or Node.js, Burp Suite or cURL, text editor (VS Code/Notepad)
